<subSubSection id="0C144DFB25FD3F62452C3BFA5C68ECE5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="type species">
<paragraph id="EF51EBB5C6099C42E91A1833625C3DBE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D558158C26885D5C79F9D4ECC0A46495" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="9D49BFAE77765BB64A17879DDCCDDFAF" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Meliturgula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meliturgula deserta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserta">Meliturgula deserta</taxonomicName>
Warncke, 1983 [1985].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4094410B29BC9B0236EC6B1CF01D81A4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="3FEB04621F32FFF8240438C426AB8491" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="584716A92C0BBD51947EB9A32168EC67" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The genus superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName id="27E8D3260460BB66C40E965EBA5C9844" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Flavomeliturgula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Flavomeliturgula" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Flavomeliturgula</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C60DBE2F872F30DE249F4A84ABABE650" authority="Engel, 2019" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Belliturgula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Belliturgula" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Belliturgula</taxonomicName>
, particularly the latter in the extensive yellow coloration. However, the genus differs from both in the short, more typical labial palpomeres in which the proximal labial palpomere is elongate, flattened, longer than the combined lengths of the remaining palpomeres (approximately 1.25
<normalizedToken id="4743937A761FAA7FD3D230E3AB62FCE6" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of remaining palpomeres combined), with the second palpomere flattened and slightly shorter than the length of the third and fourth palpomeres combined; and the third and fourth palpomeres subequal in length and cylindrical (Fig. 13). In addition, the glossa is acute (Figs 6, 15) (rather than broadly truncate apically), the glossa is shorter than the head length (Figs 6, 19-21) (rather than greater than the head length in the former two genera), the pretarsal claws are cleft (simple in the former two genera), the metasomal terga have distinctive broad setal bands (Figs 16-18) (lacking in the former two genera), and the pygidial plate is apically emarginate (Fig. 25) (acutely rounded in the former two genera). Other diagnostic traits include: small species, slightly more than 8 mm in length; integument largely pale yellow with few dark brown to black markings (Figs 6, 16-18); outer subantennal sulcus arched (Fig. 6); clypeus gently and weakly convex, scarcely protuberant (Figs 6, 17, 19), extending in front of compound eye by about 0.5
<normalizedToken id="2DF97C9919D281AB7E3076E3F775FABD" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
compound eye width; labrum wider than long, width 1.7
<normalizedToken id="F857446E8BA3ECFD00BDC9A495A4262F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length, without lateral oval windows of transparent integument (Fig. 20), surface gently and weakly convex with weak subtriangular proximal medial depression; prementum ventrally with abundant, elongate (1.0
<normalizedToken id="8D7FE176E72799C700E60A2466E97718" originalValue="–1.9×">-1.9x</normalizedToken>
median ocellar diameter), erect to suberect, simple setae (Figs 15, 19, 21); galea shorter than stipes; mesoscutum with abundant, appressed, squamose setae (Fig. 18), intermixed with sparse, erect, minutely spicate setae (0.8
<normalizedToken id="261109ADADFFE40050DCB46416516533" originalValue="–1.0×">-1.0x</normalizedToken>
median ocellar diameter); probasitarsus elongate, slender, length approximately 3
<normalizedToken id="075107698A333891680A7829C6244936" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
width; mesotibial spur about as long as mesobasitarsus; forewing with r-rs distinctly shorter than 3Rs, 1rs-m distad 1m-cu, and 1cu-a about 4
<normalizedToken id="B644B1140718F02311A2F32750E067B8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as 2M+Cu; hind wing with 10 or more distal hamuli arranged in a dense series.
</paragraph>
<caption id="7D7A830779FC8B4FF1FA5582B2AAD5F4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<paragraph id="D3E99770644BDB1594707DF260F9E745" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Figures 5-7. Female faces of representative 
<taxonomicName id="31F088AF75AC684FD22B92E8A307B506" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Meliturgulina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Meliturgulina" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subtribe" subtribe="Meliturgulina">Meliturgulina</taxonomicName>
. 5 
<taxonomicName id="AA5007AFA9D136C2DCC218D6656481DF" authority="Engel, 2019" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Belliturgula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Belliturgula najdica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="najdica">Belliturgula najdica</taxonomicName>
Engel, gen. et sp. n., from Saudi Arabia (note arched outer subantennal sulci) 6 
<taxonomicName id="F988BE9618A4D4928967AAA27BC85088" authority="Engel, 2019" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Khuzimelissa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Khuzimelissa deserta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserta">Khuzimelissa deserta</taxonomicName>
(Warncke), comb. n., from Pakistan 7 
<taxonomicName id="5E678D89A676D3526B92666F29A1FE5E" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Flavomeliturgula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Flavomeliturgula (Flavomeliturgula) lacrymosa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacrymosa" subGenus="Flavomeliturgula">Flavomeliturgula (Flavomeliturgula) lacrymosa</taxonomicName>
(Popov) from Iran (note straight outer subantennal sulci).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DBAB823156562B54982A500D3CF3E59B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="83C1FD4F2629A344A0287B2D1D0BB300" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4E73D20FD144A839BE7E5B4B7CB32BF7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The new genus-group name is a combination of Khuzi, the Middle Persian name for the ancient Susian people, and from which the regional name Khuzestan derives (and encompasses the type locality of the type species), and the Greek, 
<normalizedToken id="462918E03C8CAD8CABBF56632D6483EE" originalValue="mélissa">melissa</normalizedToken>
(μέλισσα), meaning, 
<normalizedToken id="B6DB6270070012E5BE2DDB4825265D91" originalValue="“bee”">&quot;bee&quot;</normalizedToken>
. The gender of the name is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8F32DECEC3C5CC1BDBB0F24B521C3509" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="included species">
<paragraph id="B6905EAACE5CDD4241AC5FC7814BED81" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Included species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="263A49D3B5821B592E287ED266613F6B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The genus presently includes only the type species, 
<taxonomicName id="24F8A60E4E10ABB5F391C67BC3B4A986" authority="Engel, 2019" authorityName="Engel" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Khuzimelissa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Khuzimelissa deserta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserta">Khuzimelissa deserta</taxonomicName>
(Warncke), comb. n., which has been recorded from Iran (Khuzestan) and Pakistan (Balochistan).
</paragraph>
